      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl card">
        <h2>Why Shopify merchants leave Klaviyo</h2>
      <p>A Shopify marketing command center treats leaving Klaviyo as stack infrastructure — not a single-app checkbox. Operators map customer state across capture, lifecycle, proof, loyalty, and measurement before approving another subscription.</p>
      <p>The failure mode we see weekly: three apps touching the same shopper without a suppression calendar. leaving Klaviyo only works when Sequenzy (or your lifecycle layer) knows who already received a popup offer, an SMS cart ping, and a loyalty bonus in the same afternoon.</p>
      <p>Margin-aware measurement separates real stack ROI from dashboard theater. For leaving Klaviyo, compare Shopify net sales and contribution margin after discounts — not last-click attribution inside each platform silo.</p>
      <p>Implementation discipline beats feature breadth. Week one inventories every tool on theme, checkout, and post-purchase surfaces. Week two assigns one owner to leaving Klaviyo. Week three launches with documented exclusions. Week four reconciles platform numbers with Shopify orders.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy earns the lifecycle slot because strategy speed matters when your team is also running paid, creative, and CX. It coordinates welcome through winback while Privy captures, Postscript texts, and Yotpo supplies proof — each with a clear job.</p>
      <p>Peak season governance is where stacks win or burn. Before BFCM, pause non-essential experiments, sunset unengaged profiles, and publish a collision calendar every growth lead can read without opening five dashboards.</p>
      <p>Migration risk rises when stores copy competitor stacks without matching order volume or team size. Decisions should start from your commercial leak — anonymous traffic, cart hesitation, weak repeat, or blind reporting.</p>
      <p>Agency-heavy stacks often hide missing internal ownership. Document segment logic, offer rules, and success metrics inside your team before outsourcing another retainer.</p>
      <p>Consent and compliance are stack issues, not legal footnotes. Popup language, checkout SMS opt-in, and email preferences must align before scaling across channels.</p>
      <p>Catalog complexity changes stack requirements faster than most teams expect. Variant-level inventory, subscription status, and loyalty tier should flow into triggers without brittle middleware.</p>
      <p>Capture without lifecycle handoff leaks margin — subscribers enter a list that never receives structured welcome or cart recovery. Lifecycle without capture starves the top of funnel.</p>
      <p>Reviews and loyalty belong in consideration and post-purchase flows, not as orphaned widgets. Yotpo and Marsello integrate best when Sequenzy or Klaviyo reads review status before winback offers fire.</p>
      <p>SMS is scarce urgency — not a parallel blast channel. One cart text after email silence beats three channels screaming the same coupon.</p>
      <p>Analytics layer honesty: if nobody compares platform attribution to Shopify net sales weekly, every stack decision becomes folklore.</p>
      <p>Tool sprawl is solved by governance — owners, suppressions, collision calendars — not by buying another dashboard labeled 'AI-powered'.</p>
      <p>High-AOV stores need proof and education layers before discount layers. Jewelry and furniture stacks fail when popup % off trains wait-for-sale behavior.</p>
        <h2>Merchant scenarios</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Lean DTC ($38k/mo):</strong> Privy capture → Sequenzy lifecycle → Postscript SMS for cart only. migrating off Klaviyo owned by founder; collision calendar in shared doc; weekly Shopify margin check.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Growth ($165k/mo):</strong> Justuno quiz → Sequenzy → Klaviyo VIP when data hire exists. migrating off Klaviyo split: education in Sequenzy, predictive segments in Klaviyo for drop weeks.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Proof-heavy:</strong> Yotpo reviews in browse/cart → Sequenzy post-purchase → Marsello loyalty on repeat. migrating off Klaviyo respects review submission and tier before promo.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario D — SMS-forward:</strong> Postscript recovery + Sequenzy email education. migrating off Klaviyo caps texts at one per intent window; quiet hours enforced.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario E — Consolidation:</strong> Yotpo Email & SMS suite when already on reviews/loyalty. migrating off Klaviyo audited quarterly for suite complexity vs operator hours saved.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario F — Migration:</strong> Leaving legacy sender mid-Q1; parallel suppressions 14 days; welcome+cart first. migrating off Klaviyo documented before winback migrates.</p>
        <h2>Migration checklist</h2>
        <ol class="mt-5 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-slate-300">
          <li>Export consent with timestamps and source (popup, checkout, import).</li>
          <li>Screenshot every live flow: triggers, delays, branches, suppressions.</li>
          <li>Map integrations: reviews, loyalty, subscriptions, helpdesk.</li>
          <li>Install new platform; verify Shopify sync before contact import.</li>
          <li>Rebuild welcome + cart; pause Klaviyo equivalents after QA.</li>
          <li>Parallel suppressions 14 days; migrate post-purchase, winback, replenishment.</li>
          <li>Update popups and forms to feed new lifecycle layer.</li>
          <li>Warm domain if sending infrastructure changes.</li>
        </ol>
        <h2>Pricing reality at scale</h2>
        <p>Klaviyo headline pricing: Free tier; paid from ~$20/mo. Compare total stack cost — capture + lifecycle + SMS + reviews — not one invoice. A cheaper sender with expensive SMS and duplicate capture often loses on margin.</p>
        <h2>Seven-layer stack map for migrating from Klaviyo</h2>
        <h3>Capture layer: Privy, Justuno</h3>
        <p>Popups, quizzes, exit intent feeding qualified subscribers with source tags for welcome branching. In migrating from Klaviyo, assign an owner and first-month deliverable before install. Test handoff into Sequenzy lifecycle with suppressions when popup offer already delivered.</p>
        <p>Failure mode: capture layer runs independently — shopper receives popup discount, cart email discount, and SMS discount same day. Fix with collision calendar, not more software.</p>
        <p>Operator test: can you name the single metric that proves capture layer improved margin last month? If not, pause new installs until measurement exists.</p>
